{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_romeo_ver02/data/sn84026749/100492738/1907120801/0241.xml":{"full_text":"NEW YORK\u2014STOCKS, BONDS, AND MONEY\u2014WASHINGTON\na. ia a\nSHARES ADVANGE;\nBUYERS WAITING\nFOR REACTION\nCall for Treasury State\nment Released Money\nHoarded by Banks.\nHill Shares Are Leaders\nDuring Whole Week.\nSteels Act Well.\nNEW YORK, Dec, 7.\u2014There have been\nmany tkbings in the market favorable to\nhigher prices during the last week, chief\nof which was the strengthening influ\nence of support and good buying by\nJ. Plerpont Morgan. But better than\nthat, even, was the general buying of\nthat contingent that has been waiting,\nwaiting for months for the coming of\nthe time when the tide would turn,\nknowing that it must, but always kept\noff heretofore by the utter feebleness\nof the market and the one-way trend\nof prices.\nWith the first signs of strength, the\narmy of waiters plunged in and each\nday the average of prices was higher\nthan on the preceding day. Monetary\nconditions were easler. The Hill shares\nled the iist in their advances, Reading\nmarching well to the front, and with\nthe industrials, under the leadership of\nSmelter, Copper, and the Steels, doing\nsplendidly.\nTrue there were reactions now and\nthen, but they were never serious, ex\ntending usually to a point or a little\nmore and nearly always recovered un\nder the buying that would follow.\nTraders were surprised at the con\ntinued strength of the market and pre\nuicted reactions, but they were met with\nassurances from commission houses that\non every reaction there were buyers\nwaiting and anxious to take on hold\nings.\nFor a time the expected final call of\nthe Comptreller of the Currency for a\nstatement of the condition of the na\ntional banks of the country seemed\nabout to check the movement. The\nbanks all over were getting ready for\nthe call. Some of the Western banks\nwere known to have 40 or 5 per cent re\nserves and some of the New England\nbanks even a higher percentage.\nCall Releases Money.\nWhen the call came for a statement\na: the close of business December 3, it\nreleased this \u201choarded\u201d money and\nthereafter for two days the market was\nvery strong.\nThursday, after a long upward move\nment in prices, came reports of a bad\nbank failure in Kansas City, and this\nwas followed a day later by a Pitts\nburg suspension. This was sufficient to\nScare a nervous market, but it was but\na circumstance to Wall Street. It was\neither a case of genuine Investment buy\ning or manipulation for the purposs of\nputting out a long line of stocks that\nneeded to be liquidated.\nHill Shares Strong.\nThe Hill shares were clearly a leader\nof the entire week. These properties,\nthe Great Northern and Northehn Pa\ncific, have intrinsic merit back of them.\nThey are worth as divivdend payers\nand prospective earners much more\nmoney than they are selling for. The\nadvance to date has been insignificant\nas compared with the decline. This may\nwell be said of the entire market. The\nHill shares were up on merit and the\nexpected sale of Northern Pacific's Bur\nJington interest to Great Northern.\nThe bulk of the week's hHusiness has\nbeen in Northern Pacific, Great North\nern, Reading, Union Pacific, in the\nrails, and Smelter, Copper, and the\nSteels in the industrials.\nReactions in Closing.\nAg usual -on the last day of the week,\nand for that matter on Friday after\nnoon preceding, the profit-taking was\nquite a feature, and there were some\nreactions that actually took some of\nthe gains of the week away entirely,\nbut always in the minor stocks and\nnot in the strong leaders, which held\na large part of their gains throughout.\nGreat Northern sold to 121%, as com\npared with 116% last Saturday. North\nern Facific turned 121% for high. as\ncompared with 111 a week ago today,\nwith a reaction to 119% for the close.\nerhaps 20 per cent of the business\nof the week was in Reading. It ad\nvanced over 5 points, but held but 33%\nnet gain at the close. Unlon Pacific\nclosed but a fraction higher, Penn\nviv recovered from the extreme\npi A that handicapped it for so\nlong, making an excellent advanc., and\nheld it throughout. New York Central\nd St. Paul, high-grade weaklings,\nane BY firmer in sympathy with the\nThis Lady\u2019s\nDiamond\nRing, 315 J,\n$15 Diamond\n$65 Diamond\nOthers up to $500.00.\nBAUM\u2019S, 707 7th St. N.W.\n$125 Diamond Rings. $100.00\n$175 I\nPROFITABLE INVESTMENT\nREAL ESTATE SECURITY\nAND LARGE PROFITS\nAre You Interested?\nAddress Box 29,\nWashington Times.\nNew York Stocks\n\n[Quotations furnished by Post Flagg.\nmembers of New York Stock Exchange, 133\n\u00a5F ot. nw.)\nok\nAmal, PAT senses sse\nAm. Car dy. pl...\nAm, Cotton\nAm, Smelt......cc.een.. Bg\nAm. Tobacco A nE\niin\n34\nBygnadzyuanss\nAbatonda raat thae iE\nA, T. 8. Powers vor 4,\nBalto. ORlO...ceenen\nBig. FOME.cxeessvssvsrss a\n3\nFy\n23EepSaunes\nesegyagies\nBk. Rpd. Trans. 839%\nbo\n\nA\n5\nCan. FRACHC suscsnen all]\n$:3\nChes. Ohio. .cinees.\n30% 30%\nuid i ih\n104%, 10475\nne 20 20%\n21% 20% 21%\n8 33 3\nCorn \u201cProf... .cosess \u201cend 113% 13% 113%\nDer Hudson vessel il Me 1425, 144\nenv. sess sean\nSin BBE\nEre, lat Pie ceerenes 6% 3% 36\nErle. M4 Lo we 31 XN 2% 26%\nRHO. yue use eevee. 116% 116%; 116 116\nat Nor 1 SRY 120 1214 118% 1%\nay\nansas C. Bd.......\nLouls, Nash..... ha Fi Wie 9%\nMex. 2 RR a 16% 14% 16\nMo, K. To. RP, NT B% Es\n.4 4\nLead 43% 43% 43\nNew York Central. 38 0 8 8\ny We... 38 33 33%\nNortel Western... 66%\nNorthern Pacific 121% 118% 119\nNorthwest esos diy. 338;\nPacific Mall Stp....... 23 22%\nPenn. R. R.....ccceee.. 1d 11435 113% 114\nPeople\u2019s GAB sececnese fi, 78% 73%\nRy BPresecsisesns vid Ne 4d Me\nRep. BL aaa 18 18: AW 1TH\nRep. 18 1 Pi seces 0. 190 NWN\nRep tne. as festa 15% 15 16%\nRock 2 La eens 3\u00a5p 32 NY 3\nSloss-Sheff tune 394 38 83\nSoe Line......s.. 81 80 80\nSt. L. 8 FM pfd. 28 29 2% 2\nSoutn. Pseo...... 6% T\u00e9a T\u00e9%\nSouth. RY .c.o- uu 15 1435 148g\nSouth. By pfd. 41 40 41\nTox. IPap...cosvicnsvas 2080 21 20% 205%\nTol, Bt. 1. W....H0 15 18 16\nTol., St. L. W., pfd. 35% 3% 3\nUnion: Pag...ccccsvises 118% 119 116% no\nU. 8. Leather......... 163% 16g 16\nU. 8. A Em EW Pr\nlB Bhusl....onnces ces O43\nU. S. Steel, pfd....... 883% 883 87% 88\nWabash ..ocersessssssas Sis Mik 1, 1085\nWabash, ptd.. eases J500 -1008 F 19%\nWheel 6 I. H..c- '8 3% B 8%\nWestern Unlon...... B81 61 60 60\nMISCELLANEOUS BONDS.\nXB. Bteel 5a....cucn- 54% 847% 84% 84%\nBT iBeaeeranrcins 64 63% 63%\nTobacco 4'S.....e.... 62\nCal. \u2018TI. Liecervessess\nCol. Southern..... eee 0%\n2d pfd...... 38\n\n\nS83\n143,\na\n\n\n62\n0. P. Conv. 3\u00a73 30\nCh. G. West..\nCh, M., St.\napserses Sh\nPeed\nDelaware and Hudson 4s, 97.\nDistilling Sec. C. Bs, 8814\nErte gen. 4s, 76.\nBrie cvt. 4s, S. A. 6\nErie cvt. 45, S. B., BM.\ngeneral market, but the advance has\nnot been material\na\nOn every side come better reports of\nconditions, re-employment of railroad\nhelp, re-employment of mill hands, aud\ngeneral hetterment of conditions.\n\nMoney is working easier, and the time\nis approaching when currency payments\nwill be generally resumed all over the\noomimAeArvy\nMorgan's support was not unrelfish\nIt was probably extended to make a\nmarket to sell stock. Things were\ngoing along nicely despite the Kansas\nCity and Pittsburg failures, when\nStandard Oll people took a hand to\ncheck the rise. This was on the last\ncay of the week. They checked It,\nbut did not cause any serious display\nof weakness. For a time the market\ntook the stock without much effort and\nthen, jn the final hour today, eased\noff moderately. In some cases there\nwas but little net gain during the week,\nthis being true of Copper and Smelter,\nthe latter going off after a fine rise,\non the declaration of the regular divi\ndend, which the street ac-epted as a\nbearish pointer.\n\n\nThe Steels have acted vecy well all\nweek. They are higher tocay by a\ncouple of points as a net result of the\noperations of the week, but there has\nLeen much stock sold.\n\n\nThe decline in Western Union has\nbeen stayed, 60 being the low and clos\ning.\nHoldings Being Distributed.\nIt is a fact that the distribution of\nstock Is going on every day. There ara\nhundreds, and in some cases thousands,\nof new stockholders in all the active\nleaders of the market. The public\nis tempted once more and while there\nmay be further <oclines in prices, the\nlarge line of orders at limits slightly\nbelow present prices are a bar to a\nserious decline and an assurance of a\ng\u00abod market. The dally sales are in\ncreasing and the prospecis are cer\ntainly better.\n\n\nAs an Indication of the absorption of\nshares, both in this country and abroad,\nfor investment! purpose, the case of the\nBaltimore and Ohio is quoted. Within\nthe year the Europear holders of this\ncompany have increased 20 per cent,\nthose of this country 44 per cent, those\nof the city of Baltimore 35 per cent,\nthose of the State of Maryland, out\nside of the city of Baltimore, 60 per\ncent.\nPARTICULAR MEN\n\u2014are pleased with our laundry\nwork\u2014the best of course. Syste\nmatic, thorough, painstaking work\nenables us to get your laundry\nwork out the day we promise it,\nand its quality is guaranteed. Glve\nus a trial order, you'll not regret it.\nWest End Laundry\n1723 and 1725 Pa Ave. NW.\nTelephone Main 2321\nThe famons\u2014\nHOOMAKER\nPENN. RYE\nTen years old, S135\nQ@rder by dhoanas\nGhe Shoomaker Co.\nEstablished 13.3\nun E St. N. W. Phone Mala 1153.3\nMorgan's Support Siifash.\nNEW YORI, Dec. 7.\u2014United States\nGovernment bonds:\ns coupon 104%3@\n3's registered, 1908, 100%@101%.\n\u00a5's small bonds, jt\nfo registered, 9%, 2 121.\n8 coupon, 1825, 1\nPanama 2's, re Sal 102.\nPhilippine 4's, 107%@110%.\n@104%.\nSTCCK EXCANGE BOND TRANBAC\nTIONS.\nNew York City 44s, 197, 108.\nImperial Japanese first series 4%s,\nImpertal Japanese, second series 4%s,\nImperial Japanese 4s, 79.\nAniericen Tobacco 6s, 9.\nAme icen Tobacco 4s, or\nAtlantic Coast Lire Js,\nBaltimore and Ohio She fy\nBaltimore and Ohlo\nBaltlinore and QOnlo rn Di\nvision 3s\nCentral Le U. FP. 48, 4\nCentral Lesther bs, 85.\nPennsylvania vy 0%.\nopusyivania oo ns 8734.\nReadin 9\nLake Shore 4s, 1881, 87%.\nNorth Pacific 4s, 100.\nOregon Short 3s, 107%.\nUnion ie first {'s, 100%.\nUnion Pacific convertible 3a 5\nUnited States Steel 8. F 8414,\nUnited States Steel Hh 53.\nWabash first 5's, 103%.\nWabash first 4, 48.\nWest Shore {'s, \"100.\nWestern Union \u00a7's, 90.\nTotal sales, 31,968,000.\nCOTTON 1S ERRATIC;\nFOLLOWS LIVERPOOL\nAm. Sec. and Trust..ceee.cocvvnnnans Wo 800\nNational Safe 196\nNEW YORK, Dec. 7.\u2014The cotton mar\nket continued to fluctuate in a very er\nratic manner today. There was a break\nof 3 to points in the trading because\nthe Liverpool markets again acted in a\nvery disappointing manner, and the\nnews from outside sources in the dry\ngoods trade and from Pittsburg and sev\neral other places is still of a very dis\nquieting character. The bull interests,\nhowever, continue to Ignore these con\nditions, in which rusned the marke. up\n1 to 16 points before the end of the first\nhour by a resumy \u2018on of aggressive\nbuying throughout ine option/ list on a\ncontinued heavy scale The market\nbr ke sharply at the closing on South\nern liquidation.\nPrices lost nearly all of the early\nadvance under this heavy selling, which\nwas chiefly by trade Interests.\nClosing prices weid as follows: De\ncember, 11.70@11.71; January, i1.20@11.21;\nMarch, 11.37@11.38; May, 11.46@11.47; July,\n11.37@11.88.\nThe markst closed easy.\nSTRAUS 1S CONFIDENT\nOF BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nSecretary Oscar 8. Straus, of the\nDepartment of Commercsa and Labor,\ntakes a hopeful view of business and\nindustrial conditions, as a result of his\ntalks with representatives of commer\nclal bodies who have been here this\nweek In conference with him.\nWhen asked what he thought of\nbusiness prospects, Mr. Straus sald:\n\u201cEverything is on the uplift. The out\nlook 1s excellent. The spirit shown by\neveryone is hopeful, helpful, and en\ncouraging.\u201d\u2019\nMr. Straus believes the depression\nhas passed its worst point, and (hat\nthe upgrade has been reached. He is\nconfident good results will come from\nhis conference with business men, and\nhis efforts to draw the commercial in\ntereste of the country into closer re\nlations with his department.\n\n\n\nARTHUR C. HOUGHTON JOINS\nREAL ESTATE CONCERN\nArthur C. Houghton last week asso\nciated himself with the sales depart\nment of the real estate corporation of\nWillige, Gibbg Daniel He was for\nseveral years connected with the Wash\nington Law Reporter Company, first in\nthe capacity of bookkecper and later\nas business manager. He is widely\nknown in business and church circles,\nbeing a native of Washington.\nMr, Houghton is a member of Hiram\nLodge, F, A. A. M., and is interested in\na number of local business enterprises.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, SUNDAY, DECEMBER 8, 1907.\nNew York Bond Ma-ket\nDISPLACING THE AUTO.\nRalloonacy,\nBalloonacy,\nIt is the latest fad;\nBalloonacy,\nBalloonacy,\nThe world is airship mad.\n\u2014Denver Post.\nUmbrellas For Gifts\nThe useful things are always appreciated most\nas gifts. Give an umbrella, and before you buy\none look over our line. We have the largest\nassortment in tre city and can give you a very\nnice umbrella, either natural wood or fancy\nhandle, from\n$1.00 up\nChildren\u2019s\nUmbrellas\n\nEvery child is delighted in owning its own\numbrella. We have all sizes and prices, and you\nwill be suryrised to see the elegant umbrella we\ncan give 01 for the child frem\n\nA 50C up.\nKrceger's{Umbrella Store\n\n618 9th Si. N.W, Opposite Patent Office.\nPhone Main 4834.\n\na a a J J J Jr J 2\nWashington Prices\nps\n\n2a\nCapital n Halwa 1nd I Sectste\nea oat oasis, 00%\nMergenthaler, 10\u00a7185.\nfj 2tep call\u2014Mitchell Mining, 150@%.\nWashington Rallway and electric pre.\nF ovr vad\nATR, SANETV, AVNET\nWi GRE ls ov pes vnss sap ti\nWash, Cart. 6'8...00s. esdosnan\nRAILROAD BONDS.\nCapital Hxactive RB. RR 5l.ceescnres\n110\n1\nCity and Suburban \u00a7s........ceeeue op\n\ni\n105%\n107\nWh\n\nEel\nColumbia R. R. \u00a7F'8...c.cinnirecnvenen\nColumbia 6's....... etrasasaststnsne\nMetropolitan R. R. Bre ens ensansans 1064\nWash, Ry. and Electric \u00a2s........\nMISCELLANEOUS BOND\nPotoniac Elec Lt, \u00a7'8...c0vvvencnens\nNorf. and Wash. steamboat Flee i\nChesa. and Pot. Tel. #s.........\nWashington Market 5's, 1927.\nWashington Market 6's, 1947.\nPUBLIC UTILITY STOCKS.\nSCARAL TIBEON. ann sree ssess sora 12\u00a2\nWash. Rwy. and Elec, com......... 29\nWash. Rwy. and Elec. pfd........\nNorfolk and Wash, Steamboat.....\n\n102%\na\n101%\n1044\nwe\n127\nBB\n68\n30 3M\nsean ss 8 73\nGeorgetown Gas............. 8 90\nTYPE MACHINE STOCKS.\nChesapeaxe and Potomac Tel...... 54 0\nGt. Old\nMergenthaler ..........cccccvnvmnene oe 198%\nRAARBRGRE 4onsesssessnsmmsnnbnsthensnnns Me Ws\nSener\nMINING STOCKS X\nMEAtChAlE o....socsscusisssns\nNATIONAL BANK STOCKS.\nCANAAN ER TERE RENAE SAR RR EAR aa\nPRENATAL ARRAS ae\nCY FP\nCom RE EE LET\nFarmers and Mechanics. 308\nLincoln casas nnn 12\nMetropolit&D ....crcvatescennntsnsnns soy\nRiggs\n\nones onsnssissnssstesnssnssttns 130 180\nsesenne EE LL\nSAVINGS BANK STOCKS.\nHome Bavings.......... sasssavass sacs 300\nMerch. Ag Savings tn A \u00ab38\nUnion BAVIAES....sverseerassensenans 220\nUnion TRUM .....c.cssvssscscsstnnssss a\nLoan and Trust 206\n\n\nFIRE INSURANCE \"STOCKS.\nr=]\n10\n5\n7\"\n19%\n50\n285\nMetropolitan\nPeople's .....e.. S\nPotomac\nRiggs Sasabssss se aistbanss returete Tx\nTITLE INSURANCE BTOCKS.\nColumbia ......cccouennen. 34\nReal Estate HY)\nMISCELLANEOUS STOCKS.\nGraphophone COM......covvesrcrsnn ane\nGraphophone pfd.......cccvveee \u201cesres sua\nFidelity Storage.......c..ctverersrens 119%\nSncuiity og ate vegesaserusehyes m\non Market....... asasesns sen\nUnion Trust Warrants 115%\nArlington 3%\nColumbia 13\nGomMIneTelal 1]\nCorcoran\nFlremen's ov ou\nFranklin\na\n8g\n8's\n\n\n50\n\n188\n200\n\n\nAes\noT)\nGreene Cananea............. essanes\nSREY: BE\nCapital... ..cce vee cesses PPP Aetasns 0\nWashiDgEIOR ....ccocessssmssssnssnncss 330 a0\nWashington Exchange.............. 15\nTRUST COMPANY STOCKS,\nWHITNEY COMPANIES\nG0 INTO BANKRUPTCY\nPITTSBURG, Dec. L-\u2014Involuntary\nbankruptcy proceedings were filed in the\nUnited States district court against the\nWhitney and Stephenson \u201c.mpany ard\nWhitney, Stephenson Co., of this city\ntoday.\nA petition for a receiver was also\nfiled in tho case of Whitney, Stephen\nson Co. The Colonial Trust Company\nwas appointed receiver by Judge A. G.\nDayton, the bond being fixed at $10,000.\nThe liabilities of this concern are sald\nto be $300.00 and the assets are an ac\ncount of $700,000 with the Whitney 2nf\nStephenson Company,\nThe immediate cause of the failure\nof Whitney, Stephenson Co. is gen\nerally believed to have been maturing\nobligations on November 1. One large\nloan was secured by 000 shares of\nstock of the Hostetter Coke Company,\nof which Mr. Whitney has been report\ned as owning about 14.800 sharos.\n\nNEY GONSTITUTION\nFOR PENN. SOCIETY\nAt a meeting of the Pennsylvania So\nelety in Pythian Temple last night a\nnew constitution was read and laid on\nthe table to be adopted at the next meet\ning. The death, November 18, of Fred\nerick U. Worley, a member of the so\nciety, formerly of Harrisburg, Pa., was\nreported by the secretary, E. A. Niess,\nwho was directed to write a letter of\ncondolence to the family of Mr. Wor\nley.\n\n\n1\nFollowing the businecs session a musi\ncal program was presented, including a\ntenor solo by Harry Krause; contralto\nsolo, Miss Lillian Chenoweth; violin solo,\nMark Lansburgh, accompanied by Ed\ngar Robinson; vocal tris, Mrs. Gibson,\nMiss Levers, and Miss Chenoweth, and\nselection by the Thomas Mandolin Club,\nMr. and Mrs. Austin Thomas, Miss\nMarie Beeker, Miss Lorena Booth, and\nHoward Bishop.\n\n\n\n\n\nCol. Samuel R. Strattan, president of\nthe society, presided. Refreshments\nwere served.\n\nBROKERS WATCH\nGAS G0. FIGHT\nVictory for Corporation Is\nGenerally Expected on\n\"Change.\nFair Demand for Street Rail:\nway Shares\u2014Bonds\nSteady.\nAfter a four-day holiday the Wash\nington Stock Exchange resumed busi\nness at the old stand and in much\nthe same manner 28 before the Thanks\ngiving adjournment. There was no dis\nposition to press stock wo sale and\nnone to advance prices to meet the\nviews of the hoiders of stook.\nThe fight on the gas company Is be\ning watched with much interest. The\nfirst victory for the company is by\nno means the end of the contest, indeed\nit will be waged with renewsd activity.\nThe general opinion on the stock ex\nchange rather fuvors tho belief that\nthe gus company w:ll win its fight for\nmcreased capitalization, but that it\nwil! be at the expense of quile a\nserious cut in the price of gas to con\nsumers.\nThe gas people, or the friends of the\ncompany on \u2018change, do not seem to\nthink that a out in price is at all\nserious, a \u201clittle niore air.\u201d The only\nfale of gas during the week was at 69.\nThere was a fairly good demand for\nthe shares of the Washington Railway\nand Electric Compony. A story runs\nthat there is a contest on for the con\ntrol of the road, but it is not in evi\ndence in the acticn of the market, as\nthe sales are simply of t\u2018en-share lots\nas a rule. The price has gradually im\n\u2018proved from 62 of a few weeks ago\nto 65%. There is out comparatively lit\ntle offered and thc market absorbs it\n\u2018quickly.\nMergenthaler has made a material\nimprovement during the week. It has\nagain reached 195, after dropping into\nthe 150s in sympathy with the break\ntn New York. Mitchell Mining has\nbeen steady, around\nThe bond market has been almost ne\nglected. Holders of bonds have de\ncided that they are good safe invest\nments, and where there were severai\nlots sold delly during tne period of de\npression there has been hardly any\nduring the currant week.\nThe Norfolk and Washington Steam\nship Company has declared a 10 per\ncent dividend, 7 per cent of which is\nextra and 3 per cenl regular.\nExchanges (Soe clearing\nNotes of other national\nFractional paper cur\nSHORT COPPER PRODUCTION\nPLAN OF AMALGAMATED\nin bank, viz:\nNEW YORK, Dec. 7.\u2014The Amal\ngamated Copper Company's dire\u00e9tors\ntoday decidel to continue the com\npany\u2019's present system of curtailment of\ncopper production. This means that the\nAnaconda, the Parrott, the Butte and\nBoston, and the Washoe mines, and the\nWashoe smelter will be entirely closed\nfor a time, whils the Boston and Mon\ntana mine will be kept in operation, its\nores to be smelted at the Great Falls\nsmelter.\n\n\n\n\n\n\nCapital OSE SIREUE Bi eececnssnnns ee $200,000 00\nSuni IME uss snsssntssns snp mnn 30,000 00\nUndivid~d profits, less expenses and\nDue to trust companies\nand savings banks. 12,916 18\nIndividual deposits sub\nject to cheek........... 907.900 15\nL. N. ROAD RELIEVED\nOF DEPOT OBLIGATION\nDemsnd certificates of\ndeposit 13,201 5\nMOBILE, Ala., Dec. 7.\u2014Judge Semmes\ndecided today that the Louisville and\nNashville railroad need not comply with\n\u201che Stats of Alabama's order to run its\nLaing into the Union station with other\nlines, because it would have been com\npelle to build fifteen miles of track to\nmake the change.\nNEW YORK BANK STATEMENT\nReserve on all deposits, increase,\n$6,778,075.\nReserve on da its, other United\nStates, Increase, 7,700.\nJ.oans, decrease, \"$11,882,900,\nSpecie, Increase, $3.334,100.\nLegal tenders, increase, $1,537,000.\nDeposits, decrease, $8, 431,900.\nCirculation, increase, $3,523 528.300.\nTotals\u2014Loans, $1,186,295,600; Specie,\n$173,888,700; legal tenders, $48,613,800:\nposits, $1,074,851, 400; circulation, Yo\n100; United States deposits, $7